Prosper Loan Data¶

by Luvie Curby¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

My dataset is the Prosper Loan Data. There are 113,937 rows of loans and 81 variables. I will look into about 20 variables. I wanted to explore how the market loan company's data and find insights related to the borrowers, the loan they lend and the grade represents the borrower's credit score, annual income, and among other things.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables. The loan listings are from late 2005 - 2014 with various characteristics of those loans. I selected 21 variables out of 81 and they are consisting of 10 discrete variables and 11 continuous variables.

Discrete Variables: LoanOriginationQuarter, ListingCategory, EmploymentStatus, IsBorrowerHomeowner, CreditGrade, IncomeRange, IncomeVerifiable, BorrowerState, Occupation, Term.

Continuous Variables: LoanOriginalAmount, MonthlyLoanPayment, BorrowerRate, BorrowerAPR, DebtToIncomeRation, CreditScoreRangeLower, CreditScoreRangeUpper, StatedMonthlyIncome, EmploymentStatusDuration, ProsperRating, ProsperScore.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I am most interested to see the Loan Origination Quarter and how the market loan company's data and find insights related to the borrowers, the loan they lend and the grade represents the borrower's credit score, annual income, and among other things.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

My main investigation will be into how the borrower's characteristics changed overtime as its business model and the larger lending environment evolved. The Loan Origination Quarter is critical feature base line.

#univariate plot of loan origination quarter in an order categorical type
quarter = ['Q4 2005', 'Q1 2006', 'Q2 2006', 'Q3 2006', 'Q4 2006', 'Q1 2007', 'Q2 2007', 'Q3 2007', 'Q4 2007', 'Q1 2008', 'Q2 2008', 'Q3 2008', 'Q4 2008',
          'Q2 2009', 'Q3 2009', 'Q4 2009', 'Q1 2010', 'Q2 2010', 'Q3 2010', 'Q4 2010', 'Q1 2011', 'Q2 2011', 'Q3 2011', 'Q4 2011', 'Q1 2012', 'Q2 2012', 'Q3 2012', 'Q4 2012',
          'Q1 2013', 'Q2 2013', 'Q3 2013', 'Q4 2013', 'Q1 2014']
qrt_cat = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True, categories = quarter)
prosperLoanData['LoanOriginationQuarter'] = prosperLoanData['LoanOriginationQuarter'].astype(qrt_cat)

prosperLoanData = prosperLoanData.loc[prosperLoanData['LoanOriginationQuarter'].isin(['Q4 2005', 'Q1 2006', 'Q2 2006', 'Q3 2006', 'Q4 2006', 'Q1 2007', 'Q2 2007', 'Q3 2007', 'Q4 2007', 'Q1 2008', 'Q2 2008', 'Q3 2008', 'Q4 2008',
          'Q2 2009', 'Q3 2009', 'Q4 2009', 'Q1 2010', 'Q2 2010', 'Q3 2010', 'Q4 2010', 'Q1 2011', 'Q2 2011', 'Q3 2011', 'Q4 2011', 'Q1 2012', 'Q2 2012', 'Q3 2012', 'Q4 2012',
          'Q1 2013', 'Q2 2013', 'Q3 2013', 'Q4 2013', 'Q1 2014'])]

plt.figure(figsize=(20,10))
base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
ax=sb.countplot(data=prosperLoanData, x='LoanOriginationQuarter', color=base_color)
plt.xlabel('Loan Origination Quarter')
plt.ylabel('Number of Listings')
plt.xticks(rotation=90);

What a huge difference it makes. By looking at this graph, it took 3 years for listing levels to reach the Q2 2008. Then, there is a big dip from Q4 2008 - 2009. After doing some research on Wikipedia, this time period concurs with the fall of the market in Fall 2008 with the huge effect by the collapse of the major investment firm Lehman Brothers and, the succeeding fallout in the global financial system. It appears the Prosper business was susceptible to the global economic crisis. We'll explore more data with the LOQ later at the Bivariate.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

• There is a strong positive relationship between credit score and loan amount. The larger the loan, the higher the credit score.

• I see a negative relationship between loan amount and interest rate. The larger the loan, the lower the interest rate on average, mostly because of borrowers have higher credit scores.

• Most of the borrowers with lower monthly income have higher debt to income ratio. That was mostly due they borrow more money.

• From Q4 2005, Prosper took 3 years for listing levels to reach the Q2 2008. Then, there is a big dip from Q4 2008 - 2009, even until 2010. This time period concurs with the fall of the market in Fall 2008 with the huge effect by the collapse of the major investment firm Lehman Brothers and, the succeeding fallout in the global financial system. It appears the Prosper business was susceptible to the global economic crisis.

• Looking at the credit score over time, it is clear that Prosper changed its policies from one that had no minimum credit score to one that had very strict lower limits. That lower limit rose over time from 520 in Q2 2007 to 600 in Q3 2009 (after the credit crisis) to 640 most recently.

• Debt consolidation is the highest number of loans, it also what demonstrated the largest loan amount.

• A strong positive relationship between term and loan amount. The longer the term, the larger the loan amount.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

I observed the self-employed is second highest with loan amount (not accounting the "Other".) Since personal loans for self-employed are harder to get, borrowers must have required something extra to convince the lender to approve a request for money.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

The credit scores distinguished borrowers by worthiness when looking at the loan amounts vs interest rate. It shows the majority of the loans are with 3-year term and they are mostly the current and completed loans. Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

Prior to 2008, it looks like prosper did not capture the loan category, and debt consolidation dominated the category subsequently every year. The influence of borrower interest rate and term in over time was clear. There was a correlation between interest rate and terms (36 and 60) from year 2012 to 2014 where the 36 term is not necessarily more expensive. I saw the prosper struggle initially with their first few years of loans. But their business grew very quickly after the downturn and market fall by 2009. Their main loan exposures are in debt consolidation and I’m sure the low interest rate environment has helped the supply of lenders looking for yield. Also, the income ranges uptick in loans in 2012-2013. It grew initially in 50k-75k, 75k-100k, and 100k+.
